[start section id="20112"]

#1 Stage III, T3, N1 colorectal cancer
I reviewed her pathology.  It looks like her pathology report is showing grade 3 out of 4 moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma forming a 2.0- x 1.2- x 0.3-cm mass and a tumor invading through the muscularis propria into the pericolonic fat.  There were 3 out of 12 regional lymph nodes that were positive.  The uterus, ovary, and the fallopian tube are not involved by the tumor.  The margin was negative.  This was consistent with stage IIIB colorectal cancer.  I discussed with the patient and family our central approach will be giving adjuvant chemotherapy to stage III colorectal cancer in the format of FOLFOX.  This involves three-drug combination with 5-FU, leucovorin, and oxaliplatin.  I went through the common side-effects associated with the three drugs.  Unfortunately, Mrs. Miller still has open wound, so I am a little concerned starting chemo in this setting.  The plan is to have her come back in one-to-two weeks, reassess her clinical status.  If her wound is healed by that time then we would potentially consider chemotherapy. However, if her wound is not totally recovered then we may have to forego the adjuvant chemotherapy.  All the questions were answered.  Patient expressed good understanding and satisfaction.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

[end section id="20112"]

